: \\end{aligned}\r\n- Step 17: $$\r\n- Step 18: Because this work is equal to $m g h$, we have\r\n- Step 19: $$\r\n- Step 20: \\begin{aligned}\r\n- Step 21: m g h & =\\frac{3 G m M_m r^2}{2 D^3} \\\\\r\n- Step 22: h & =\\frac{3 G M_m r^2}{2 g D^3}\r\n- Step 23: \\end{aligned}\r\n- Step 24: $$\r\n- Step 25: Note that the mass $m$ cancels, and the value of $h$ does not depend on $m$.\n- Step 26: Nor does it depend on the substance, so to the extent Earth is plastic, similar tidal effects should be (and are) observed for the surface land.\n- Step 27: If we insert the known values of the constants into the Equation, we find\r\n- Step 28: $$\r\n- Step 29: h=\\frac{3\\left(6.67 \\times 10^{-11} \\mathrm{~m}^3 / \\mathrm{kg} \\cdot \\mathrm{s}^2\\right)\\left(7.350 \\times 10^{22} \\mathrm{~kg}\\right)\\left(6.37 \\times 10^6 \\mathrm{~m}\\right)^2}{2\\left(9.80 \\mathrm{~m} / \\mathrm{s}^2\\right)\\left(3.84 \\times 10^8 \\mathrm{~m}\\right)^3}=0.54 \\mathrm{~m}\r\n- Step 30: $$\n\nEXPLANATION:\nTo solve this, We continue to use our simple model of the ocean surrounding Earth. After computing, the result is 0.54 m.\n\nANSWER: 0.54 m"}]}
